explanation:
`int.TryParse` returns `true`/`false` and avoids exceptions on invalid input. The parsed value is returned via the `out` parameter.

Example:
```csharp
if (int.TryParse(str, out var n)) {
    Console.WriteLine($"Value: {n}");
} else {
    Console.WriteLine("Invalid number");
}
```
Contrast with `int.Parse`, which throws on bad input:
```csharp
int x = int.Parse("abc"); // FormatException
```

Use `int?` to represent a nullable value type (it can be either an `int` or `null`).

Examples:
```csharp
int? maybeAge = null;
if (maybeAge.HasValue) {
    Console.WriteLine(maybeAge.Value);
}
int age = maybeAge ?? 0; // null-coalescing: uses 0 if null
```
